      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Both laws ask the same question: at a given temperature, how many identical particles occupy a single-particle state of energy E?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.21,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:39:28"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "For fermions, the denominator contains plus one. The occupation never exceeds one per complete single-particle state. At low temperature, states fill from the bottom upward.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "trace"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.5,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:39:28"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The result approaches a sharp Fermi step: occupied below the chemical potential, empty above it, with a narrow thermal blur around the edge.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "transform"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.15,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:39:28"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 6,
      "narration_text": "Fermions stack across states. They do not stack inside one state.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 4.16,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:39:28"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "For bosons, the denominator contains minus one. There is no Pauli cap: a single state may hold one boson, ten, a thousand, or macroscopically many.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.37,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:39:28"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Near the lowest allowed energy, the Bose occupation can surge upward. At low enough temperature and under the right conditions, many bosons collect in the ground state.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "trace"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.81,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:39:28"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Put the curves on the same dimensionless energy axis. The Fermi curve is bounded by one; the Bose curve rises without that bound as energy approaches the chemical potential from above.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.01,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:39:28"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "The domain matters: the ordinary Bose occupation formula is read for energy above the chemical potential. Drawing it through the pole would invent negative occupations.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "trace"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.15,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:39:28"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "At high temperature and low density, the exponential dominates the plus or minus one. Both laws then approach the same classical Maxwell–Boltzmann tail.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "converge"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.66,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:39:28"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The sign is compact bookkeeping for a deeper distinction: antisymmetric fermion states exclude, while symmetric boson states permit collective occupation.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.47,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:39:28"
      }
    },
